      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Compassion"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_ariosto_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_orlando_furioso"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Non è finto il destrier, ma naturale, / ch’una giumenta generò d’un grifo: / simile al padre avea la piuma e l’ale, / li piedi anteriori, il capo e il grifo; / in tutte l’altre membra parea quale / era la madre, e chiamasi ippogrifo; / che nei monti Rifei vengon, ma rari, / molto di lá dagli aghiacciati mari.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": [
        "Canto IV",
        "paragraph 18"
      ],
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_hippogriff_ariosto"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:int_antlion_septuagint",
      "@type": "beast:Interpretation",
      "beast:appearsIn": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_septuagint"
      },
      "beast:hasTextualReference": {
        "@id": "beastiary:citation_job_4_11"
      },
      "beast:ofCreature": {
        "@id": "beastiary:creature_antlion"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_peter_pan_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_peter_pan"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Tink was not all bad: or, rather, she was all bad just now, sometimes she was all good. Fairies have to be one thing or the other, because being so small they unfortunately have room for one feeling only at a time.",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_fairy_disney"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_theophilus_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_schedula_theophilus"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "the heathen, who are said to be skilled in this art, produce basilisks for themselves in this way. They have a structure under the ground [...] In this they place two old fowls, twelve or fifteen years old, and they give them plenty to eat. When they have become plump, with the heat of their fatness they copulate and lay eggs. When these have been laid, the fowls are taken away and toads are introduced to sit on the eggs, and bread is given them for food. When the eggs are hatched, male chicks emerge like hens' chicks. After seven days they grow the tails of serpents.",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_basilisk_theophilus"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:archetype_pride",
      "@type": "beast:Archetype",
      "beast:hasMeaning": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Overweening self-exaltation, the vice of superbia. archetype_prima_materia The alchemical first matter, the base substance of transformation."
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:source_the_hobbit",
      "@type": "beast:LiteraryWork",
      "dcterms:language": "en",
      "dcterms:title": "The Hobbit",
      "schema:creator": {
        "@id": "beastiary:person_tolkien"
      },
      "schema:dateCreated": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#gYear",
        "@value": "1937"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_tolkien_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_the_hobbit"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "There he lay, a vast red-golden dragon, fast asleep; thrumming came from his jaws and nostrils, and wisps of smoke, but his fires were low in slumber. Beneath him, under all his limbs and his huge coiled tail, and about him on all sides stretching away across the unseen floors, lay countless piles of precious things, gold wrought and unwrought, gems and jewels, and silver red-stained in the ruddy light. Smaug lay, with wings folded like an immeasurable bat, turned partly on one side, so that the hobbit could see his underparts and his long pale belly crusted with gems and fragments of gold from his long lying on his costly bed. Behind him where the walls were nearest could dimly be seen coats of mail, helms and axes, swords and spears hanging; and there in rows stood great jars and vessels filled with a wealth that could not be guessed.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Chapter 12",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_dragon_tolkien"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:part_snake_hair",
      "@type": "beast:AnatomicalPart",
      "beast:belongsToImaginaryStructure": {
        "@id": "beast:SchizomorphicStructure"
      },
      "beast:embodiesImaginarySymbol": {
        "@id": "beast:TeriomorphicSymbol"
      },
      "beast:isGovernedBy": {
        "@id": "beast:DiurnalRegime"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The snake is a teriomorphic animal in Durand's Imaginary, and Medusa's writhing serpent-locks embed feral, biting animal terror directly into the body."
      }
    },
