      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:person_rowling",
      "@type": "schema:Person",
      "foaf:familyName": "Rowling",
      "foaf:givenName": "J. K.",
      "schema:birthDate": "1965",
      "schema:nationality": "English",
      "schema:sameAs": [
        {
          "@id": "http://viaf.org/viaf/http://viaf.org/viaf/116796842"
        },
        {
          "@id": "wd:Q34660"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_shelley_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_on_the_medusa"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "I. / It lieth, gazing on the midnight sky, / Upon the cloudy mountain-peak supine; / Below, far lands are seen tremblingly; / Its horror and its beauty are divine. / Upon its lips and eyelids seems to lie / Loveliness like a shadow, from which shine, / Fiery and lurid, struggling underneath, / The agonies of anguish and of death. / II. / Yet it is less the horror than the grace / Which turns the gazer's spirit into stone, / Whereon the lineaments of that dead face / Are graven, till the characters be grown / Into itself, and thought no more can trace; / 'Tis the melodious hue of beauty thrown / Athwart the darkness and the glare of pain, / Which humanize and harmonize the strain. / III. / And from its head as from one body grow, / As grass out of a watery rock, / Hairs which are vipers, and they curl and flow / And their long tangles in each other lock, / And with unending involutions show / Their mailed radiance, as it were to mock / The torture and the death within, and saw / The solid air with many a ragged jaw. / IV. / And, from a stone beside, a poisonous eft / Peeps idly into those Gorgonian eyes; / Whilst in the air a ghastly bat, bereft / Of sense, has flitted with a mad surprise / Out of the cave this hideous light had cleft, / And he comes hastening like a moth that hies / After a taper; and the midnight sky / Flares, a light more dread than obscurity. / V. / 'Tis the tempestuous loveliness of terror; / For from the serpents gleams a brazen glare / Kindled by that inextricable error, / Which makes a thrilling vapour of the air / Become a and ever-shifting mirror / Of all the beauty and the terror there-- / A woman's countenance, with serpent-locks, / Gazing in death on Heaven from those wet rocks.",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_medusa_shelley"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_sturluson_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_prose_edda"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Trolls call me moon of dwelling-Rungnir, giant's wealth-sucker, storm-sun's bale, seeress's friendly companion, guardian of corpse-fiord, swallower of heaven-wheel; what is a troll other than that?",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Paragraph 53",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_troll_prose_edda"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_andersen_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_andersen"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "They were six beautiful children; but the youngest was the prettiest of them all; her skin was as clear and delicate as a rose-leaf, and her eyes as blue as the deepest sea; but, like all the others, she had no feet, and her body ended in a fish's tail.'",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_siren_andersen"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:ability_hypnotic_gaze",
      "@type": "beast:Ability",
      "beast:belongsToImaginaryStructure": {
        "@id": "beast:SchizomorphicStructure"
      },
      "beast:embodiesImaginarySymbol": {
        "@id": "beast:NyctomorphicSymbol"
      },
      "beast:isGovernedBy": {
        "@id": "beast:DiurnalRegime"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The entrancing gaze draws its victim down into shadow, sleep, and loss of self, enacting the nyctomorphic engulfment by darkness."
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:etymology_minotaur",
      "@type": "beast:Etymology",
      "beast:hasMeaning": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Compound of Minos (Μίνως) and tauros (ταῦρος) meaning bull. Literally Bull of Minos."
      },
