    {
      "@id": "beastiary:ability_resolution",
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Firmness of will and steadfast determination; the creature's resolute, unyielding disposition, located by the bestiaries in the head as the seat of its resolve."
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Resolution"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_omero_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_odissea_omero"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Alle Sirene presso tu giungere devi anzitutto, / che tutti quanti gli uomini incantan che giungono ad esse. / Chi s’avvicina a loro, mal cauto, ed ascolta la voce / delle Sirene, quello non mai la sua sposa ed i figli / piú lo vedranno tornare, diletto mai piú non ne avranno; / ma le Sirene, incanto gli fan con le limpide voci, / sedute sopra un prato. D’intorno c’è d’ossa un gran mucchio, / d’uomini putrescenti, di scheletri e pelli aggrinzite.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": [
        "Book XII",
        "verses 39-46"
      ],
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_siren_omero"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_dante_paradiso_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_dante_paradiso"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Parea dinanzi a me con l’ali aperte / la bella image che nel dolce frui / liete facevan l’anime conserte; / parea ciascuna rubinetto in cui / raggio di sole ardesse sì acceso, / che ne’ miei occhi rifrangesse lui. / E quel che mi convien ritrar testeso, / non portò voce mai, né scrisse incostro, / né fu per fantasia già mai compreso; / ch’io vidi e anche udi’ parlar lo rostro, / e sonar ne la voce e «io» e «mio», / quand’ era nel concetto e ’noi’ e ’nostro’.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": [
        "Canto XIX",
        "verses 1-12"
      ],
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_eagle_dante"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_rowling_2",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_harry_potter_book_3"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Trotting toward them were a dozen of the most bizarre creatures Harry had ever seen. They had the bodies, hind legs, and tails of horses, but the front legs, wings, and heads of what seemed to be giant eagles, with cruel, steel-colored beaks and large, brilliantly, orange eyes. The talons on their front legs were half a foot long and deadly looking. Each of the beasts had a thick leather collar around its neck, which was attached to a long chain, and the ends of all of these were held in the vast hands of Hagrid, who came jogging into the paddock behind the creatures.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Chapter 6",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_hippogriff_rowling_harry"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:habitat_desert",
      "@type": "beast:RealWorldPlace",
      "beast:habitatCategory": {
        "@id": "beast:habitat_terrestrial"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "An arid expanse of sand and barren ground."
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Desert"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:int_snake_aberdeen",
      "@type": "beast:Interpretation",
      "beast:additionalAbility": [
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:ability_blindness"
        },
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:ability_skin_shedding"
        }
      ],
      "beast:additionalPart": [
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:part_eyes_on_temples"
        },
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:part_moist_body"
        }
      ],
      "beast:appearsIn": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_aberdeen_bestiary"
      },
      "beast:belongsToImaginaryStructure": {
        "@id": "beast:SyntheticStructure"
      },
      "beast:embodiesArchetype": {
        "@id": "beastiary:archetype_rebirth"
      },
      "beast:embodiesImaginarySymbol": {
        "@id": "beast:CyclicalSymbol"
      },
      "beast:hasNarrativeFunction": {
        "@id": "beastiary:function_exemplum"
      },
      "beast:hasTextualReference": {
        "@id": "beastiary:citation_aberdeen_4"
      },
      "beast:isGovernedBy": {
        "@id": "beast:NocturnalRegime"
      },
      "beast:ofCreature": {
        "@id": "beastiary:creature_snake"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The snake's sloughing of its old skin to regain youth, allegorized as the believer shedding the 'old self' for new life, embodies the cyclical symbol of renewal where casting off the old is the condition of rebirth."
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_rowling_10",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_harry_potter_book_1"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "A centaur was standing over him, not Ronan or Bane; this one looked younger; he had white-blond hair and a palomino body. [...] The centaur didn’t answer. He had astonishingly blue eyes, like pale sapphires. He looked carefully at Harry, his eyes lingering on the scar which stood out, livid, on Harry’s forehead. ‘You are the Potter boy,’ he said. ‘You had better get back to Hagrid. The Forest is not safe at this time – especially for you. Can you ride? It will be quicker this way.'",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Chapter 15",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
